of
all
the
follies
and
absurdities
by
which
some
part
of
her
family
were
connected
with
that
corps.
Not
a
syllable
had
ever
reached
her
of
Miss
Darcy's
meditated
elopement.
To
no
creature
had
it
been
revealed,
where
secrecy
was
possible,
except
to
Elizabeth;
and
from
all
Bingley's
connections
her
brother
was
particularly
anxious
to
conceal
it,
from
the
very
wish
which
Elizabeth
had
long
ago
attributed
to
him,
of
their
becoming
hereafter
her
own.
He
had
certainly
formed
such
a
plan,
and
without
meaning
that
it
should
